# PPT HTML Generation

You are generating one slide of presentation HTML.

Use this skill after the task already has:

- a single-page layout from the outline
- a deck-level style definition or equivalent style constraints
- available picture references
- the current page index and total page count

This skill also applies to delegated work packages or subtasks such as:

- generate all HTML slides from `outline.json`
- read `style.json` and render `page_01.html` to `page_N.html`
- implement PPT pages in a specified deck directory

The output must be HTML only.

## Core objective

Generate a visually strong but implementation-safe single-slide HTML page for a `1280x720` presentation canvas.

## Required inputs

You should have:

- `style`
- `layout`
- `picture2` or equivalent picture mapping
- `current_page`
- `total_pages`

## Style JSON handling

Before writing any HTML or CSS, inspect the actual `style.json` keys first. Never assume a schema.

- Do not assume keys such as `primary_blue`, `secondary_blue`, `accent_cyan`, `headings`, or `body_text`.
- If the current `style.json` shape differs from your expectation, normalize it first. Do not fall back to an unrelated default light theme just because a key name differs.
- If you need fallback values, derive them from values that already exist in the current `style.json` so the visual direction stays consistent.

Real schemas that must be handled include:

1. `typography.title_strategy.font_family_css` / `typography.body_strategy.font_family_css`
2. `typography.heading.font_family` / `typography.body.font_family`
3. `typography.headings.family` / `typography.body_text.family`

Do the same for colors by inspecting the actual structure first. Common variants include:

1. `color_palette` as an array with role-based entries
2. `color_palette.background/accent/text`
3. `color_palette.primary_blue/secondary_blue/...`

If a required style value is still unclear, do not silently switch to a generic white background plus blue accent theme. Keep the closest possible visual direction implied by the provided style.

## Hard layout rules

### Fixed canvas

- The page must be exactly `1280x720`.
- No scrollbar is allowed.
- All content must fit in the viewport.
- Any scaling logic must live on the outer container, never on inner content blocks.

### Layout mechanics

- Use Flexbox or CSS Grid for alignment.
- Do not use `mt-auto`, `flex-grow`, or `flex: 1` to fake spacing.
- Do not use `position: absolute` plus `transform: translate(...)` for flow content.
- Image and chart regions should be controlled by explicit size logic, not empty spacer divs.

### Footer safe area

- Reserve the lower-right `160px x 60px` area for the page number.
- No content may overlap that area.
- Page number must be in `<div id="footer">`.
- Footer must include inline positioning equivalent to `position: absolute; right: 40px; bottom: 20px;`.

## Page structure

The HTML must follow a two-layer wrapper structure:

- `.wrapper`
- `#bg` as background layer
- `#ct` as content layer
- `#footer` as page number layer

Both `#bg` and `#ct` should fill the full page.

## Element identity rules

Every major content element should have:

- a unique id such as `text_1`, `chart_1`, `table_1`, `svg_1`
- a class that describes its type

For charts:

- use a `div` container only
- initialize ECharts on that `div`

## Picture and decoration rules

### External pictures

- Only use provided picture references.
- Do not use network images directly.
- Keep the picture id exactly aligned with the expected picture id from layout.
- Do not embed real image URLs in the generated HTML if later processing will inject them.
- If `image_selection.json` or equivalent metadata provides a successful local picture path, prefer that local file.
- If a page has `needed_pictures`, the final HTML must explicitly consume that requirement. Do not silently drop the picture just because the layout is `grid`, `timeline`, `two_column`, `three_column`, `closing`, or another non-classic image layout.
- If the local picture download succeeded, the final HTML must contain a local image reference such as `images/...`.
- If the download failed, keep a visible placeholder tied to the intended visual described in `needed_pictures[].description` rather than omitting the image region.
- Even on non-image-centric pages, integrate the picture as a background module, side card, inset illustration, or closing hero visual instead of deleting it.

### Decorative graphics

- Prefer CSS-drawn shapes.
- Background pictures belong in `#bg`.
- Background visuals should preserve readability.

### Filtering

- If a picture region is too small to matter, drop it instead of forcing it in.

## Chart rules

- Use `ECharts` or `Frappe Gantt`.
- Do not use Chart.js.
- Do not use `<canvas>` as the chart container.
- Chart containers must explicitly declare width and height.

## Text and table rules

- Do not semantically modify, shrink, or omit layout text.
- Adapt font size and spacing to avoid overflow.
- Tables must fit without scrollbars.

## Output rules

- Output HTML only.
- No markdown fences.
- No natural language explanation.

Use this skeleton as the baseline shape:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <meta charset="utf-8"/>
    <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/echarts@5.4.3/dist/echarts.min.js"></script>
    <style>
        * { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }
        body { margin: 0; display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; background: #333; min-height: 100vh; overflow: hidden; }
        .wrapper { width: 1280px; height: 720px; position: relative; overflow: hidden; background: #fff; box-shadow: 0 0 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.5); }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="wrapper">
        <div id="bg" style="position: absolute; inset: 0; z-index: 1;"></div>
        <div id="ct" style="position: absolute; inset: 0; z-index: 2; padding: 40px 60px;"></div>
        <div id="footer" class="footer-page" style="position: absolute; right: 40px; bottom: 20px; z-index: 10;">
            1 / N
        </div>
    </div>
    <script>
        // echarts init
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

## Final quality bar

- strong visual hierarchy
- no overflow
- no footer collision
- stable rendering
- consistent with the provided style
- faithful to the single-page layout input
- pages with `needed_pictures` must not end up with successfully downloaded images that are never referenced in the final HTML
